## 🔬 Advanced TypeScript

This lesson explores powerful TypeScript features used in professional codebases: mapped types, conditional types, template literals, decorators, and module augmentation.

---

## 1️⃣ Mapped Types

Transform every property of an existing type:

```typescript
type Readonly<T> = { readonly [K in keyof T]: T[K] }
type Optional<T> = { [K in keyof T]?: T[K] }
type Nullable<T> = { [K in keyof T]: T[K] | null }

// Real-world: make all string properties uppercase brand
type UppercaseKeys<T> = {
  [K in keyof T as Uppercase<string & K>]: T[K]
}
// UppercaseKeys<{ name: string }> → { NAME: string }
```

---

## 2️⃣ Conditional Types

Types that work like ternary expressions:

```typescript
type IsString<T> = T extends string ? true : false
type IsString<string>  // true
type IsString<number>  // false

// Infer within conditional types
type UnwrapPromise<T> = T extends Promise<infer U> ? U : T
type Result = UnwrapPromise<Promise<string>>  // string
type Result2 = UnwrapPromise<number>          // number (not a Promise)

// Distributive conditional types
type NonNullable<T> = T extends null | undefined ? never : T
type Clean = NonNullable<string | null | undefined>  // string
```

---

## 3️⃣ Template Literal Types

```typescript
type EventName<T extends string> = `on${Capitalize<T>}`
type ClickEvent = EventName<"click">  // "onClick"
type KeyEvent = EventName<"keydown">  // "onKeydown"

// Building type-safe event handlers
type ButtonEvents = EventName<"click" | "focus" | "blur">
// "onClick" | "onFocus" | "onBlur"

// Type-safe CSS properties
type CSSDirection = "Top" | "Right" | "Bottom" | "Left"
type MarginProperty = `margin${CSSDirection}`
// "marginTop" | "marginRight" | "marginBottom" | "marginLeft"
```

---

## 4️⃣ `infer` Keyword

Extract types from within other types:

```typescript
type ReturnType<T> = T extends (...args: any[]) => infer R ? R : never
type Fn = () => string
type Result = ReturnType<Fn>  // string

// Extract array element type
type ArrayElement<T> = T extends Array<infer E> ? E : never
type Elem = ArrayElement<string[]>  // string
```

---

## 5️⃣ Type Guards (Advanced)

```typescript
// User-defined type guard function
function isUser(obj: unknown): obj is User {
  return typeof obj === "object" 
    && obj !== null 
    && "id" in obj 
    && "email" in obj
}

// Usage
function processData(data: unknown) {
  if (isUser(data)) {
    console.log(data.email)  // TypeScript knows data is User here
  }
}

// Assertion functions (throws if invalid, narrows type)
function assertIsString(val: unknown): asserts val is string {
  if (typeof val !== "string") throw new Error("Not a string!")
}
```

---

## 6️⃣ Declaration Merging & Module Augmentation

Extend existing types from external libraries:

```typescript
// Extend Express Request to include user data
declare namespace Express {
  interface Request {
    user?: { id: string; role: string }
  }
}

// Augment an existing module
declare module "axios" {
  interface AxiosRequestConfig {
    _retry?: boolean
  }
}
```

---

## 7️⃣ Discriminated Unions (Pattern)

The most powerful pattern for handling multiple state shapes:

```typescript
type AsyncState<T> =
  | { status: "idle" }
  | { status: "loading" }
  | { status: "success"; data: T }
  | { status: "error"; error: Error }

function renderUser(state: AsyncState<User>) {
  switch (state.status) {
    case "idle":    return null
    case "loading": return <Spinner />
    case "error":   return <Error message={state.error.message} />
    case "success": return <UserCard user={state.data} />
  }
}
```

TypeScript knows the exact shape within each `case`.

---

## 8️⃣ `satisfies` Operator (TS 4.9+)

Validates an expression against a type without losing the specific inferred type:

```typescript
type Routes = Record<string, { path: string; exact?: boolean }>

// 'satisfies' validates the object is a valid Route
// but preserves the literal types for IDE support
const routes = {
  home:  { path: "/" },
  about: { path: "/about", exact: true },
} satisfies Routes

// TypeScript knows routes.home.path is "/" (not just string)
```

---

## 9️⃣ `never` Type

`never` represents values that should never occur:

```typescript
// Exhaustiveness checking — ensures all union cases are handled
function assertNever(val: never): never {
  throw new Error(`Unhandled case: ${JSON.stringify(val)}`)
}

type Color = "red" | "blue" | "green"
function getHex(color: Color): string {
  switch (color) {
    case "red":   return "#ff0000"
    case "blue":  return "#0000ff"
    case "green": return "#00ff00"
    default:      return assertNever(color)  // TypeScript error if case missing!
  }
}
```

---

## 🔟 Overloads

Provide multiple function signatures for different argument combinations:

```typescript
// Overload signatures
function formatDate(date: Date): string
function formatDate(date: string): Date
function formatDate(date: Date | string): string | Date {
  if (typeof date === "string") return new Date(date)
  return date.toISOString()
}

const d: Date = formatDate("2024-01-01")   // TypeScript knows it returns Date
const s: string = formatDate(new Date())    // TypeScript knows it returns string
```

---

## 💡 Summary

| Feature | Use Case |
|---|---|
| Mapped types | Transform all properties of a type |
| Conditional types | Type-level ternary expressions |
| Template literals | Type-safe string patterns |
| `infer` | Extract inner types |
| Type guards | Narrow types at runtime |
| Discriminated unions | Model state machines cleanly |
| `satisfies` | Validate while preserving inference |
| `never` | Exhaustiveness checking |
| Overloads | Multiple function signatures |
